ought of as pruning","html_id":"matching-better-thought-of-as-pruning","implicit":true,"key":"xkirYfcfj4"}],"key":"Xdb5Ql2Jpg"},{"type":"block","kind":"notebook-content","data":{},"children":[{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":1,"column":1},"end":{"line":1,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"When you hear the term “matching”, your first thought is probably that the focus of the method is finding pairs of observations that are similar, and... you’re not ","position":{"start":{"line":1,"column":1},"end":{"line":1,"column":1}},"key":"aCA9VyiafC"},{"type":"emphasis","position":{"start":{"line":1,"column":1},"end":{"line":1,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"wrong","position":{"start":{"line":1,"column":1},"end":{"line":1,"column":1}},"key":"Fuc3CMBCxD"}],"key":"Gy5dlhsor4"},{"type":"text","value":". But a better way to think of matching is as a method for ","position":{"start":{"line":1,"column":1},"end":{"line":1,"column":1}},"key":"ojGb3jLVya"},{"type":"emphasis","position":{"start":{"line":1,"column":1},"end":{"line":1,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"pruning","position":{"start":{"line":1,"column":1},"end":{"line":1,"column":1}},"key":"o55UHGEehW"}],"key":"KqXFQvlJaW"},{"type":"text","value":" observations that don’t have any close matches.","position":{"start":{"line":1,"column":1},"end":{"line":1,"column":1}},"key":"bVtvyZAPlj"}],"key":"bYfGqps8qH"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":3,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"In other words, at its core, matching is about pruning back your dataset until you’re left with control and treatment observations that look relatively similar. Any control observations that are completely unlike any treatment observation (in terms of our explanatory variables) you drop, and any treatment observations that are completely unlike any controls you drop.","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":3,"column":1}},"key":"GIXjHW9ZFX"}],"key":"lkxWLolv3p"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":5,"column":1},"end":{"line":5,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"So if we ran matching here, we’d end up with the following dataset (dropped observations greyed out) (matching isn’t deterministic, there are choices, but a reasonably matching algorithm would likely do something like this):","position":{"start":{"line":5,"column":1},"end":{"line":5,"column":1}},"key":"xciPjhGOft"}],"key":"JSiFaPyecG"}],"key":"Sccay7pRwS"},{"type":"block","kind":"notebook-content","data":{},"children":[{"type":"image","url":"/matching_king_4-a16465012df4481f908edeb7e9eb821a.png","alt":"matching_king_4","position":{"start":{"line":1,"column":1},"end":{"line":1,"column":1}},"key":"AraCGyhp6z","urlSource":"images/matching_king_4.png"}],"key":"VoL07ulct8"},{"type":"block","kind":"notebook-content","data":{},"children":[{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":1,"column":1},"end":{"line":1,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"As you can see, we’ve now dropped all the control observations that are completely unlike our treatment variables. And now the range of Education for control variables and treatment variables is about the same -- we have a “balanced” dataset.","position":{"start":{"line":1,"column":1},"end":{"line":1,"column":1}},"key":"OdF4NYgRTA"}],"key":"srS0K2Jwko"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":3,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"And now it doesn’t matter if we do a simple linear fit or if we include a quadratic term -- the results look exactly the same (i.e. no model dependence):","position":{"start":{"line":3,"column":1},"end":{"line":3,"column":1}},"key":"zASDul9kAs"}],"key":"HSPtC7DvuJ"}],"key":"uwGtCuaIhD"},{"type":"block","kind":"notebook-content","data":{},"children":[{"type":"image","url":"/matching_king_5-2ee4650d876165e89d5c72e66a7d97d5.png","alt":"matching_king_5","position":{"start":{"line"